WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.520
Welcome to The Test Set. Here we talk with some of the brightest thinkers and tinkerers

00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:11.560
in statistical analysis, scientific computing, and machine learning, digging into what makes

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:17.799
them tick, plus the insights, experiments, and OMG moments that shape the field.

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:23.200
This episode is part 1 of a conversation with Wes Mckinney, open source software developer,

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:29.280
author, metalhead, and principal architect at Posit. I'm Michael Chow. Thanks for joining

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:35.439
us. All right, Wes, thanks for coming on The Test Set. I'm so — yeah, I feel so

00:00:35.439 --> 00:00:42.080
privileged and honored to be able to interview you about your contributions to the Python

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:46.360
open source ecosystem. And just to be doing this podcast with you, I feel like is a really

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:53.639
incredible opportunity. Maybe to start out, do you mind just catching everybody in the

00:00:53.639 --> 00:00:57.439
world up on sort of what you've worked on?

00:00:57.439 --> 00:01:07.879
Well, happy to be here. And yeah, well, it's been a lot of projects over time, but I definitely

00:01:07.879 --> 00:01:12.000
get asked about this a lot. It's like, how did you start building pandas? And it was

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.279
— we were just talking earlier today, I think it was 17 years ago this month that

00:01:16.279 --> 00:01:23.919
I started working on the code base that became pandas. But I got interested in Python as

00:01:23.919 --> 00:01:29.639
a programming language in my first job out of school. I was a math major and had a little

00:01:29.639 --> 00:01:33.480
bit of programming experience, but not much. I didn't do computer science. I took a couple

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:40.160
of theoretical computer science classes in college. But then I got a job in quant finance

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:44.199
and thought that I would be doing financial modeling and stuff like that. It turns out

00:01:44.199 --> 00:01:49.400
I was doing a lot of data processing and data analysis, data cleaning, that kind of thing.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:53.599
And I found that working with data was fairly frustrating. And so I initially became really

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:57.480
interested in how I could build tools for myself to make myself more productive and

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:06.120
make it easier to work with data. And I was very influenced by the R ecosystem, R circa

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:11.559
2008. So this was a really long time ago. Like the tidyverse didn't exist yet. There

00:02:11.559 --> 00:02:15.679
was ggplot2, but there was no dplyr. A lot of the things that we now take for granted

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:20.320
didn't really exist. And the development environment, there was no RStudio either.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:26.880
So it was also like R was much more primordial in those days. And I was doing a lot of SQL.

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:34.759
And so I started building Pandas, which initially was an internal project at AQR where I worked.

00:02:34.759 --> 00:02:40.679
I eventually got permission to release that as an open source project. And so I spent

00:02:40.679 --> 00:02:46.080
a couple of years working on Pandas a little bit on the side. It didn't get really that

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:54.759
popular until maybe 2011, 2012 when I switched to being a grad student in statistics. So

00:02:54.759 --> 00:02:58.559
I was interested in becoming a statistician because I wanted to get better at data science

00:02:58.559 --> 00:03:04.440
by learning about statistics. But I saw that Python was getting more popular. And I just

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:08.880
felt like I need to figure out how to work full time on Pandas and to help grow this

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:13.559
ecosystem. And so it was around that time that I started writing Python for data analysis.

00:03:13.559 --> 00:03:18.839
I ended up dropping out of my PhD and working on Pandas full time. I recruited a couple

00:03:18.839 --> 00:03:25.600
of my colleagues from AQR to come and work with me on that. And so that was 2011. I released

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:32.679
my book, Python for Data Analysis, in 2012. And then I started doing a hybrid of open

00:03:32.679 --> 00:03:37.199
source development and entrepreneurship because I was trying to figure out how can I build

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:41.039
businesses or create some kind of business model to support the open source development

00:03:41.039 --> 00:03:48.839
that I was doing. So I ended up founding a company in 2013 with Changshu, who was one

00:03:48.839 --> 00:03:54.080
of the first contributors to Pandas. That wasn't me. He was also at AQR. And so we went

00:03:54.080 --> 00:04:00.839
on. So we did that startup. We ended up getting acquired, acquihired by Cloudera. And so I

00:04:00.839 --> 00:04:07.399
was at Cloudera. A group of us started the Apache Arrow project, which is entering its

00:04:07.399 --> 00:04:12.360
10th year of development now. And so that was a big focus for many years, right around

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:17.440
the time that we started the Arrow project. You mentioned IBIS. So Arrow was more about

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:23.200
like building a better computational foundation for data science, for data frame libraries,

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:28.000
but also for interacting with databases in the outside world, file formats, all that

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.559
fun stuff. And IBIS was a Python project that was about building a richer user interface

00:04:34.559 --> 00:04:39.959
for translating between like the composable data frame concepts that people were familiar

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:46.519
with with Pandas, but bridging that into the SQL database and data warehouse world, which

00:04:46.519 --> 00:04:53.480
I was seeing a lot of in the big data ecosystem. And so IBIS is still an active and in development

00:04:53.480 --> 00:05:00.119
project. I'm not working on it so much lately. I feel like there's so much. It's just a tremendous

00:05:00.119 --> 00:05:04.679
amount of work. And I feel like it's so neat. One thing that really stuck out to me is a

00:05:04.679 --> 00:05:11.799
lot of the history and not just the creation, which I think you hit on a bit, but all the

00:05:11.799 --> 00:05:18.640
organizing and getting people together. The first most impressive, maybe not the most

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:23.440
impressive example of organizing, but the first case that really stuck out to me was

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:29.440
your time speed running. And I don't want to take away from the other things, but I

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:36.600
almost do feel like I'd love to explore just all the organizing you've done and almost

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:41.640
maybe starting there and working forward to the Python DECO system.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:44.760
This is going back in another decade.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:47.160
Just like dial it back one more.

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:51.679
So in the late 90s, there was a video game that came out in 1997 called GoldenEye 007.

00:05:51.679 --> 00:05:57.440
And it was one of the most popular console first person shooters that was ever, I think

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:03.959
it was the first really popular console first person shooter that came out. And it developed

00:06:03.959 --> 00:06:10.880
this cult following, which included me. And for some weird reason, the developers had

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:16.440
included this feature in the game where it would show you the fastest time where you

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:21.720
beat each level. And I discovered the speed running community when it already existed.

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:28.040
There was a website run by this fellow, Glenn McDiarmid in Australia, where it assembled

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:32.279
people's fastest times playing the game. And for whatever reason, I was really attracted

00:06:32.279 --> 00:06:37.359
to helping that community thrive and grow. And there was an opportunity for me to take

00:06:37.359 --> 00:06:42.279
over stewardship of the community and run it for a couple of years. And so I didn't

00:06:42.279 --> 00:06:47.959
really know that much about web development, but I really did enjoy, as you said, the community

00:06:47.959 --> 00:06:53.839
development aspect of building processes and thinking about the governance and how

00:06:53.839 --> 00:06:58.320
we make decisions. If you suspect that somebody is cheating at the game, we had to create

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:02.959
processes like submit videotapes and digitize the videotapes and put them online. So that

00:07:02.959 --> 00:07:10.040
was my first exposure to community development and building that speed running community.

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:15.119
But yeah, so in a sense, when I later got involved in open source development, some

00:07:15.119 --> 00:07:21.320
of those behaviors were familiar to me from having been active for a few years in that.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:27.640
And when you were getting involved, how did you find this community? And what stood out

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:34.239
to you the most? Being part of the speed running community, what really drew you to it, would

00:07:34.239 --> 00:07:35.239
you say?

00:07:35.239 --> 00:07:43.399
I mean, I think the people in it were mostly interacting through both email and eventually

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:49.519
message boards. Eventually we had a message board. This was pre-Slack and pre-Discord,

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:56.600
way ancient history. But I found that the people in the community, I felt that they

00:07:56.600 --> 00:08:01.519
were a lot like me, that they liked video games and they were interested in technology

00:08:01.519 --> 00:08:07.920
and the internet. And the fact that we don't know how to create the right tools and systems

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:14.600
to create this speed running ecosystem and to make it function, but we'll figure it out

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:15.600
together.

